<subSubSection id="A28678F8DAAED06E34F59EB9DEC09DCA" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="22B302A3757CF89C343231D95ADDC84D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C4526E3AD6553E5097463D4AB1DAD1F0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="C563575E8C5C8CE07A218B29A71D227F" genus="Tritium" lsidName="Tritium aestivum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aestivum">
<emphasis id="1DF0841C5CFE30AA9A9370A9271F196B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Tritium aestivum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(wheat), 
<taxonomicName id="A06ACDE11FEB1D32CC08947005C31688" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Oryza" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Oryza sativa" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">
<emphasis id="6CD61DF09A92F524DB149C34770FB2A2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Oryza sativa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(rice), 
<taxonomicName id="97BB17564CD4275CA09F7D908FEF1BFD" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Sacharum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sacharum officinarium" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="officinarium">
<emphasis id="BFF977C6421B85453D7A340E5239FA96" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Sacharum officinarium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(sugarcane), 
<taxonomicName id="E770DD37A0578E67994D3F078AA81DA6" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Echinochloa" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Echinochloa colona" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="colona">
<emphasis id="01B9D6C0A6EF5F4E0BED33417C5E851F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Echinochloa colona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cultivated field) are all affected by this pest. It seems rare in numbers, and not widely occurring like other species of 
<taxonomicName id="1B4F15A7B3AF6202FF81AE0FD4DFE9AB" authorityName="Laicharting" authorityYear="1781" class="Aves" family="Trochilidae" genus="Gryllidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gryllidae" order="Apodiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gryllidae</taxonomicName>
. These specimens were collected from rice fields whereas other plants such as sugarcane and wheat were also present, but with minor damage.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EB3110342072AAD5BEA6F003827EC910" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="02ACA4160B74C38830D5AE7A0535F44B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Global distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D5323AA5C67579ED84B5C94B8415BB22" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Denmark, Germany, Netherlands, Switzerland, UK, Pakistan (
<bibRefCitation id="1B1B06299ADE3AD49944C2F7814B1DFD" author="Cigliano, MM" journalOrPublisher="The Zoological Survey of India, Calcutta" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://Orthoptera.SpeciesFile.org" refId="B6" refString="Cigliano, MM, Braun, H, Eades, DC, Otte, D, 2020. Orthoptera species file online, version 5.0/5.0. http://Orthoptera.SpeciesFile.org" title="Orthoptera species file online, version 5.0 / 5.0." url="http://Orthoptera.SpeciesFile.org" year="2020">Cigliano et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="454CF6C7C4728575F95ECE80F2EE945A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="2FACD788601BCF348734B207FAA1CBAD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="907871FD8E0DBBB268F666B4399BBCD8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Due to its rare status and sporadic nature 
<taxonomicName id="6AD6BC2579677478415ABB4324630E0F" genus="G." lsidName="G. (G.) campestris" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="campestris" subGenus="G.">G. (G.) campestris</taxonomicName>
is included in the red lists 
<bibRefCitation id="EAC6C954B17633938FA707BD248C8A6D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10531-006-9123-9" author="Hochkirch, A" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity Conservation" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="3597 - 3607" refId="B11" refString="Hochkirch, A, Witzenberger, KA, Teerling, A, Niemeyer, F, 2007. Translocation of an endangered insect species, the field cricket (Gryllus campestris Linnaeus 1758) in northern Germany. Biodiversity Conservation 12: 3597 - 3607, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10531-006-9123-9" title="Translocation of an endangered insect species, the field cricket (Gryllus campestris Linnaeus 1758) in northern Germany." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10531-006-9123-9" volume="12" year="2007">Hochkirch et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. It is flightless in its habitat of dune, short grasses, chalky soil, and light sandy porous soils. During our field survey we collected material from different districts. Our examination demonstrates that this species has morphological similarity to 
<taxonomicName id="22972820924502542D422EF106C7E6CF" genus="G." lsidName="G. (Gryllus) bimaculatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="bimaculatus" subGenus="Gryllus">G. (Gryllus) bimaculatus</taxonomicName>
but few differences in wing pattern and head morphology identifies each species.
</paragraph>
